trends. Ekaterina V. Haskins argues that these developments are driven not only by the weaponization of the official memory of World War II but also by familial pieties and deep-seated habits of memory. Haskins uncovers how widely shared practices of remembrance have taken root and flourished through recurring exposure to war films, urban environments, popular commemorative rituals, and digital archives. Combining scholarship and personal biography, Haskins illuminates why, despite the staggering toll of World War II and internal political violence on Soviet families, most Russian citizens continue to proudly embrace their family’s participation in the war effort and avoid discussion of domestic political persecution. Elegantly written and convincingly argued, this book is an important intervention into contemporary rhetoric and memory studies that will also appeal to broader audiences interested in Russia, Eastern Europe, and the war in Ukraine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCollective memoryzRussia (Federation). 0aMemoryxPolitical aspectszRussia (Federation). 0aPolitical violencezSoviet Union. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zSoviet UnionxInfluence. 7aHISTORY / Russia / Post-Soviet.2bisacsh  aRussia.  aSoviet state terror.  aStalinism.  aUkraine war.  aWWII.  aWorld War II.  acollective memory.  afamily memory.  amemory habits.  amemory studies.  apopular appeal of the cult of Soviet victory.  arhetorical studies.  athe Great Patriotic War.  athe Soviet Union.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271098487?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271098487423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271098487/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles